05843nam a22009975i 9780520940918DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20052005cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021696787  a97805209409187 a10.1525/97805209409182doi  a(DE-B1597)519743  a(OCoLC)1062914427  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aE98.R3 4aE98.R3bS56 2006eb 7aREL0290002bisacsh04a323.44/2/089970732221 aSmith, Huston, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Seat at the Table :bHuston Smith In Conversation with Native Americans on Religious Freedom /cHuston Smith; ed. by Phil Cousineau. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (253 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tPREFACE -- tPREFACE -- tINTRODUCTION THE PRIMAL RELIGIONS -- t1. THE SPIRITUAL MALAISE IN AMERICA -- t2. FIVE HUNDRED NATIONS WITHIN ONE -- t3. ECOLOGY AND SPIRITUALITY -- t4. THE HOMELANDS OF RELIGION -- t5. NATIVE LANGUAGE, NATIVE SPIRITUALITY -- t6. THE TRIUMPH OF THE NATIVE AMERICAN CHURCH -- t7. THE FIGHT FOR NATIVE AMERICAN PRISONERS’ RIGHTS -- t8. STEALING OUR SPIRIT -- t9. THE FIGHT FOR MOUNT GRAHAM -- t10. REDEEMING THE FUTURE -- t11. THE HEALING OF INDIAN COUNTRY -- tAFTERWORD -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this collection of illuminating conversations, renowned historian of world religions Huston Smith invites ten influential American Indian spiritual and political leaders to talk about their five-hundred-year struggle for religious freedom. Their intimate, impassioned dialogues yield profound insights into one of the most striking cases of tragic irony in history: the country that prides itself on religious freedom has resolutely denied those same rights to its own indigenous people. With remarkable erudition and curiosity—and respectfully framing his questions in light of the revelation that his discovery of Native American religion helped him round out his views of the world's religions—Smith skillfully helps reveal the depth of the speakers' knowledge and experience. American Indian leaders Vine Deloria, Jr. (Standing Rock Sioux), Winona LaDuke (Anishshinaabeg), Walter Echo-Hawk (Pawnee), Frank Dayish, Jr. (Navajo), Charlotte Black Elk (Oglala Lakota), Douglas George-Kanentiio (Mohawk-Iroquois), Lenny Foster (Dine/Navajo), Tonya Gonnella Frichner (Onondaga), Anthony Guy Lopez (Lakota-Sioux), and Oren Lyons (Onondaga) provide an impressive overview of the critical issues facing the Native American community today. Their ideas about spirituality, politics, relations with the U.S. government, their place in American society, and the continuing vitality of their communities give voice to a population that is all too often ignored in contemporary discourse. The culture they describe is not a relic of the past, nor a historical curiosity, but a living tradition that continues to shape Native American lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFreedom of religionzUnited States. 0aIndians of North AmericaxReligion. 7aRELIGION / Ethnic & Tribal.2bisacsh  aamerican government.  aamerican society.  aanishinaabeg.  acommunity.  aecology.  afree exercise of religion.  aindigenous peoples.  aindigenous religion.  airoquois.  akinship.  alakota.  alaw.  amohawk.  anative american culture.  anative american religions.  anative americans.  anative peoples.  anavajo.  aoglala lakota.  aonondaga.  apawnee.  apolitics.  areligion.  areligious ceremony.  areligious freedom.  areligious justice.  asioux.  aspiritual law.  asp